Cell.Text: Just what my mother told me. I've also studied a little bit on my own, but there's not much. | When something is trapped in a soul gem, and then the energy is expended to imbue an item with power, the remnants are sent here.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05SoulCairnBranchTopic: Do you know anything about this place?

Cell.Text: Well, I think it's specifically the black ones. I don't know if the Soul Cairn claims the remainder of just any old gem.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05SoulCairnBranchTopic01: Any soul gem?

Cell.Text: [S] Just look at this place. Do you think anything would want to live here? | The only things that can survive here are the Ideal Masters, the undead and the souls themselves. Well, if you want to call that "living."

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05SoulCairnBranchTopic02: Does anything live here?

Cell.Text: I don't think anyone's ever met the Ideal Masters. I'm not even sure anyone knows what they look like. | They could be underground, flying above us... They might be the ground. I have no idea.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05IdealMastersBranchTopic: Do you think we'll meet the Ideal Masters?

Cell.Text: Lots of theories. Some say they feed on them like I feed on blood. | Others think they use them as payment to an even higher power... almost like a currency. A very strange currency. | Whatever they're doing with them, they've been harvesting for millennia. No telling how many souls are trapped here.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05IdealMastersBranchTopic01: Why are they collecting these souls?

Cell.Text: Look around you. There are some extremely powerful undead here. | Even a necromancer as seasoned as my mother would be willing to spend years trying to gain access to them.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05IdealMastersBranchTopic02: Why would a necromancer want to deal with them?

Cell.Text: Exactly. It's a lost art. Most necromancers just raise up whatever bodies are nearby. A simple trick, really. Child's play. | But bringing something from the Soul Cairn gives you something much more powerful.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05IdealMastersBranchTopic03: Summon them you mean?

Cell.Text: Well, that's usually the trick. It's possible to do it through a simple portal. | But to finalize the deal, you have to travel here yourself... and most of them never come back.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05IdealMastersBranchTopic04: How do the necromancers communicate with them?

Cell.Text: No, but there's no way she would have left it in Tamriel. | She wanted to get it as far away from my father as possible. I can't imagine a better place.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05MomScrollBranchTopic: Are you sure Valerica has the Elder Scroll?

Cell.Text: Then we find out where she hid it. If she's still alive... well, as alive as she was before. Or is now. Or... you know what I mean.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05MomScrollBranchTopic01: And if she doesn't?

Cell.Text: Probably to avoid whatever my father would do to her if he could get his hands on her. | Or maybe her plan was to come back, but she was stuck here. We won't know until we find her.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05MomScrollBranchTopic02: Why not hide it here and then return?

Cell.Text: Relieved... I think. | All those things had been building for a while. You have no idea how long I wanted to say that to her.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic: How are you feeling after talking to your mother?

Cell.Text: Look, I loved my father, but when he found that prophecy... that became his life. Everything else, even me and my mother... we just became clutter. | I was close with my mother, but she just kept feeding me her opinions of him, and eventually I started believing them.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic01: Why did you ever agree to her plan?

Cell.Text: The moment we gave ourselves to Molag-Bal, things got really icy between them. | They were both drunk with power, and pulling in different directions. | Then he found that prophecy, and... that was it.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic02: She doesn't seem too fond of him.

Cell.Text: I was. Honestly, it took me up until now to figure out that my mother was really just as bad as he was. | He was obsessed with power. She was obsessed with seeing him fail. It was just so... toxic. | Maybe I could have seen this coming. We could all be better off now.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic03: And you were caught in the middle.

Cell.Text: Like I said, we were never very close. Not a lot of father-daughter bonding if you know what I mean. | But once we threw our lot in with Molag-Bal... people just don't think about their families anymore. "Power takes precedence," he always said.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic2a: It sounds like you already didn't like him much.

Cell.Text: [S] You don't know what it's like, coming from a family like that. | Everything eventually tumbles down to you.
[S] I know that in my head. But I just can't help feeling bad about... the way things are. | Sorry, I know you're trying to help. Thanks.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic4a: You shouldn't blame yourself.

Cell.Text: G|Anyway, we should keep moving.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchGoodbye

Cell.Text: [S] That's easy to say, but I definitely didn't help things.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic4b: It probably didn't have anything to do with you.

Cell.Text: [S] Oh, they definitely were. | I just wonder if that meant it was my job to be giving.
[S] Definitely. You must think my life has been so strange. It sounds like your family wasn't nearly as fractured as mine.

Node.Caption: DLC1VQ05RelationshipBranchTopic4c: It sounds like they were both being selfish.
